{
  "doc_id": "52449",
  "text": "The identification of a mammalian iron siderophore [CITATION_1] suggests that LCN2 may function as a mammalian iron-scavenging strategy. In order to examine whether LCN2 may promote small intestinal tumor size by increasing iron availability to the tumor, we examined iron content in the tumor. As stored iron, predominantly existing as iron(III) in ferritin, may be more susceptible to physiological fluctuations, [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] we chose to focus on iron(II) where LCN2 also has a demonstrated effect. [CITATION_4] From paired mice, we excised size-and location-matched adenomas and quantified iron(II) content by atomic-absorption spectrometry. We found that adenomas from Lcn2 À / À mice had a statistically significant reduction in iron(II) content compared with those from Lcn2 þ / þ mice (P ¼ 0.011, n ¼ 10). To better examine the nature of this defect, we segregated the adenomas based on their location of excision (Figure 5b) .",
